      "targetText": "publicitate"
    }
  ],
  "antonyms": [
    {
      "sourceText": "hide",
      "targetText": "a ascunde"
    }
  ],
  "examples": [
    {
      "sourceText": "I show the results.",
      "targetText": "Eu arăt rezultatele."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "Do you show the information?",
      "targetText": "Arăți informațiile?"
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "He shows the advertisement.",
      "targetText": "El arată reclama."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "We show the new advertisement.",
      "targetText": "Noi arătăm noua reclamă."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "Do you (plural) show the results?",
      "targetText": "Arătați rezultatele?"
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "They show the trends.",
      "targetText": "Ei arată tendințele."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "I have shown the data.",
      "targetText": "Am arătat datele."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "He showed the results.",
      "targetText": "El arăta rezultatele."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "I will show the next slide.",
      "targetText": "Voi arăta următoarea diapozitiv."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "I would like to show the graph.",
      "targetText": "Aș dori să arăt graficul."
    },
    {
      "sourceText": "Show me the information!",
      "targetText": "Arată-mi informațiile!"
    }
  ],
  "learningTips": [
    {
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "Remember 'show' as in a TV show where things are presented visually, just like 'a arăta' means to make visible."
    },
    {
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "Think of 'show' and 'a arăta' both starting with a vowel sound and involving making something clear or visible."
    },
    {
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "The English word 'show' is short and simple, just like the Romanian 'arăta' which is easy to remember once you associate it with 'to show'."
    },
    {
      "lang": "en",
      "text": "Imagine you 'show' a friend a picture, and in Romanian you say 'Eu arăt o poză' – both mean to display or present something."
    }
  ],
